{
  "doc_id": "51904",
  "text": "We have previously shown that infection of C57Bl/6 mice with a highly virulent strain of M. avium (strain ATCC 25291 SmT) induces profound peripheral T cell depletion and premature thymic atrophy [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and that M. avium is able to progressively infect the thymus [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Since IFN is a key molecule in peripheral lymphocyte loss we aimed at analyzing the role of this cytokine in mycobacterial infection-induced thymic atrophy. Moreover, IFN is known to cause the up-regulation of the inducible nitric oxide synthase (iNOS) in mycobacterial infection [CITATION_5] and nitric oxide has been shown to synergize with corticosterone in the induction of apoptosis of thymocytes in in vitro experiments [CITATION_6] . Thus, we also aimed at determining if nitric oxide was leading to thymic atrophy during mycobacterial infection. IFN induced macrophage activation and the resulting increase in iNOS activity were identified as a major mechanism responsible for M. avium induced thymic involution. Moreover, we show that IFN-induced thymic atrophy synergized with corticosterone signaling.",
